{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":529763,"duration_api_ms":710198,"num_turns":4,"result":"Here's a summary of the key findings across all four research areas:\n\n**Critical actionable issues discovered:**\n\n1. **No SIGINT trap** — Ctrl+C leaves all `claude -p` subprocesses running and spending money. Add `trap 'kill 0' EXIT; trap 'exit 130' INT` to `ultrainit.sh`.\n\n2. **`--bare` not used** — target project's CLAUDE.md and hooks contaminate analysis agents. All `run_agent()` calls should include `--bare`.\n\n3. **`gensub` portability gap** — `gensub()` is gawk-only; macOS stock awk and mawk don't have it. The `check_dependencies()` in `lib/config.sh` checks that `awk` exists but not that it's gawk.\n\n4. **`sed -i` incompatibility** — GNU (`sed -i 'expr'`) and BSD (`sed -i '' 'expr'`) are mutually exclusive syntax. Use the tmpfile-then-move pattern instead.\n\n5. **bats helper libraries unpinned** — `bats-support`, `bats-assert`, `bats-file` are installed from `HEAD` in `Dockerfile.test` while `bats-core` is pinned to `v1.11.1`. Non-deterministic.\n\n**Non-obvious behaviors to know:**\n\n- `--json-schema` uses a post-generation retry loop, not constrained decoding. Complex schemas with many required fields increase retry probability and cost. The failure subtype is `error_max_structured_output_retries`.\n- `--allowedTools 'Bash(git:*)'` — the space before `*` is significant. It matches `git log` but not a hypothetical binary named `gitfoo`.\n- Budget check in parallel runs is optimistic: all N agents check budget simultaneously before any `.cost` files are written, so overrun by up to N×agent_budget is possible.\n- `setup_file` variables need `export` to reach `@test` bodies under `--jobs N`. The current `_common_setup` in `setup()` pattern is already correct.","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"bd26a769-400c-4f7c-90ed-ed7f94e880f2","total_cost_usd":2.3776380999999995,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":46659,"cache_read_input_tokens":68807,"output_tokens":6479,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":46659,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1,"output_tokens":501,"cache_read_input_tokens":41789,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4870,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4870},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":202183,"outputTokens":22977,"cacheReadInputTokens":870345,"cacheCreationInputTokens":422376,"webSearchRequests":24,"costUSD":1.1720724999999999,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000},"claude-sonnet-4-6":{"inputTokens":2784,"outputTokens":17895,"cacheReadInputTokens":1410937,"cacheCreationInputTokens":134802,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":1.2055656000000001,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000}},"permission_denials":[{"tool_name":"Bash","tool_use_id":"toolu_01FmUoBP1itSueGm2vLjMKLG","tool_input":{"command":"bash --version | head -1","description":"Check current bash version"}},{"tool_name":"Bash","tool_use_id":"toolu_017Dp75vxjSUZjp1peYejT5o","tool_input":{"command":"head -20 /home/joelbarmettler/projects/ultrainit/.github/workflows/*.yml 2>/dev/null | head -40"}},{"tool_name":"Bash","tool_use_id":"toolu_01HnEpCTc1wWHxf4f97BavX9","tool_input":{"command":"wc -l /home/joelbarmettler/projects/ultrainit/lib/*.sh /home/joelbarmettler/projects/ultrainit/ultrainit.sh"}}],"structured_output":{"domain_knowledge":[{"concept":"Process group management for parallel agent cleanup","relevance":"ultrainit spawns 8+ background `claude -p` processes in parallel via `run_agents_parallel`. Without a trap, Ctrl+C orphans all child processes — they keep running and keep spending money.","code_mapping":"lib/agent.sh `run_agents_parallel()` — add `trap 'kill 0' EXIT; trap 'exit 130' INT; trap 'exit 143' TERM` to ultrainit.sh startup. `kill 0` sends SIGTERM to all PIDs in the current process group, which includes all backgrounded child scripts since job control is off in non-interactive shells."},{"concept":"Claude CLI `--bare` flag suppresses target project's .claude/ config","relevance":"When ultrainit agents analyze a *target* project that itself has a `.claude/` directory with skills, hooks, and CLAUDE.md, those are loaded by `claude -p` during the agent run. This contaminates agent behavior — the target's CLAUDE.md instructions apply to the analysis agent. `--bare` disables this.","code_mapping":"lib/agent.sh `run_agent()` — the `claude -p` invocation should include `--bare` to skip loading the target project's `.claude/` config, MCP servers, hooks, and memory during analysis. Needs empirical verification that structured output still works under `--bare`."},{"concept":"`--json-schema` triggers post-generation retry loop, not constrained decoding","relevance":"Claude generates free-form text first, then the CLI validates against the schema. On validation failure it retries (up to ~3 times). This means complex schemas with many required fields increase retry probability and cost. The subtype `error_max_structured_output_retries` signals exhaustion.","code_mapping":"schemas/*.json — keep schemas focused and avoid deeply nested required arrays. lib/agent.sh error handling already checks `is_error` and extracts `.errors[]`; the `error_max_structured_output_retries` subtype should be surfaced specifically in `diagnose_phase_failure()`."},{"concept":"Claude CLI JSON output envelope fields","relevance":"The structured output envelope is `{is_error, subtype, result, structured_output, total_cost_usd, duration_ms, duration_api_ms, num_turns, session_id}`. `structured_output` is only populated when `--json-schema` is passed. Budget exhaustion produces `{errors:[...], subtype:'error_max_budget_usd', is_error:true}`.","code_mapping":"lib/agent.sh — the current `.structured_output // .result // .` jq extraction is correct. The `total_cost_usd` extraction for `record_cost()` is correct. The `.errors` array handling for budget exhaustion messages is also already in place."},{"concept":"`--allowedTools` pattern syntax — the space before `*` is semantically significant","relevance":"`Bash(git:*)` matches any bash command whose text starts with `git ` (with space). It would NOT match a hypothetical command named `git-forensics` (no space). `Bash(git commit:*)` matches `git commit -m 'msg'` but not `git commit-tree`. Understanding this prevents over-permissioning agents.","code_mapping":"lib/gather.sh and lib/research.sh — the `--allowedTools` strings passed to `run_agent`. The git-forensics agent uses `Bash(git:*)` which is correct and intentional."},{"concept":"bats-core `setup_file` variable scoping in parallel runs","relevance":"Variables set in `setup_file` are NOT automatically visible inside `@test` bodies when bats runs with `--jobs N`. They must be exported or written to `$BATS_SUITE_TMPDIR`. Using `setup()` (per-test) instead of `setup_file()` avoids this trap.","code_mapping":"tests/helpers/test_helper.bash — `_common_setup()` is correctly called from `setup()` (per-test), not from `setup_file()`. This is the right pattern. New test files should follow the same convention."},{"concept":"Heredoc delimiter collision risk in bundle.sh","relevance":"If any bundled file contains a line that exactly matches the closing heredoc delimiter (alone on a line), the heredoc terminates early and silently produces a truncated extraction. The `__EOF_LIB_agent__` style delimiters are long enough to be unlikely, but not guaranteed safe against content that happens to match.","code_mapping":"bundle.sh — consider switching embedded file content to `base64 -w0` (Linux) / `base64` (macOS, no wrapping by default) encoding to eliminate delimiter collision entirely. Note: `base64 -w0` is GNU-only; BSD base64 uses `-b 0` or defaults to no wrapping."},{"concept":"PID reuse race in `spin()` spinner loop","relevance":"The `kill -0 \"$pid\"` polling in `spin()` checks if the background process is still alive. Once the OS reaps the process, the PID can be immediately recycled. A newly spawned unrelated process could match the same PID, causing the spinner to loop indefinitely. Harmless in practice given Linux pid_max, but the fix is to check `wait -n` availability or use `$!` captured before the poll.","code_mapping":"lib/utils.sh `spin()` — the `while kill -0 \"$pid\" 2>/dev/null` loop. Low-priority fix: capture exit status from a background subshell or use a sentinel file written by the child on completion."}],"framework_practices":[{"framework":"bats-core","version":"1.11.1 (pinned in Dockerfile.test)","practice":"Use `bats_require_minimum_version 1.7.0` at top of each .bats file to make version requirements explicit and catch regressions if someone runs tests against an older local bats installation outside Docker.","relevance":"The `run -0`/`run -N` implicit status checking syntax and `--filter-tags` were both added in 1.7.x/1.8.x. Without the guard, a developer running `bats` locally with an older version would get misleading silent failures."},{"framework":"bats-core","version":"1.11.1","practice":"Use `BATS_NO_PARALLELIZE_WITHIN_FILE=true` in `setup_file` for any test file where individual tests share tmpdir state (write then read). Within-file parallelism under `--jobs N` can cause races even with per-test `mktemp -d`.","relevance":"tests/unit/ files that use `_common_setup` create isolated `TEST_TMPDIR` per test, so within-file parallelism is safe. But future test files that use `$BATS_SUITE_TMPDIR` for cross-test state would need this guard."},{"framework":"bats-core","version":"1.7.0+","practice":"`run -0 cmd` is a shorthand for `run cmd; assert_success`. Use the longform `run cmd; assert_success` in all ultrainit tests to remain compatible with older bats if anyone runs outside Docker, and to make intent explicit.","relevance":"tests/unit/ and tests/edge/ currently use the explicit longform, which is correct. New tests should continue this pattern."},{"framework":"bash","version":"5.x (Docker base: bash:5 Alpine)","practice":"macOS ships bash 3.2.57 (GPL2 frozen). Features available in bash 5 but not bash 3.2: associative arrays (`declare -A`), `wait -n`, `wait -p`, `mapfile`/`readarray`, `**` globbing. Any of these in lib/*.sh will silently break on stock macOS.","relevance":"lib/config.sh uses indexed arrays extensively. `check_dependencies()` checks bash version for Windows only — should also warn macOS users who haven't installed a newer bash via Homebrew. The `run_agents_parallel()` temp-script pattern avoids `wait -n`, keeping bash 3.2 compatibility."},{"framework":"bash","version":"3.2+ compatible","practice":"Never use `wait -n` (bash 4.3+) or `wait -p` (bash 5.1+) in ultrainit lib files. The current approach of saving PIDs to an array and iterating `wait \"$pid\"` is the maximally portable pattern for collecting per-process exit codes.","relevance":"lib/agent.sh `run_agents_parallel()` — already correctly uses the array-of-PIDs + individual wait pattern. Preserve this in future modifications."},{"framework":"GNU coreutils / BSD utils","version":"macOS default: BSD; Linux: GNU","practice":"`sed -i` differs fatally: GNU needs `sed -i 's/.../.../'`, BSD needs `sed -i '' 's/.../...'`. The two forms are mutually incompatible. Use `tmp=$(mktemp); sed ... <file >\"$tmp\"; mv \"$tmp\" file` for portable in-place editing without platform detection.","relevance":"lib/merge.sh and lib/validate.sh — audit every `sed -i` call. utils.sh `iso_date()` already has a correct portable fallback pattern (`date -Iseconds 2>/dev/null || date +%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%S%z`). Apply the same pattern to sed."},{"framework":"GNU awk / BSD awk","version":"Docker installs gawk explicitly; macOS ships nawk","practice":"`gensub(regex, replacement, n, string)` is gawk-only. BSD awk (macOS `/usr/bin/awk`) and mawk (some Debian/Ubuntu) do not have it. Add a gawk capability probe to `check_dependencies()`: `awk 'BEGIN{gensub(/a/,\"b\",\"g\",\"test\")}' /dev/null 2>/dev/null || log_error 'need gawk'`.","relevance":"lib/config.sh, lib/merge.sh — any awk invocation using `gensub` will fail silently on macOS stock awk. The Dockerfile correctly installs `gawk` but `check_dependencies()` only verifies that `awk` exists, not that it is gawk."},{"framework":"GitHub Releases / curl-pipe-bash distribution","version":"current","practice":"Publish a `ultrainit.sh.sha256` file alongside each release artifact, containing the SHA256 of the bundle. Include a one-liner in the README that downloads both, verifies, and only then executes. This does not prevent CDN compromise but prevents accidental download corruption.","relevance":"The current README uses raw `curl -sL ... | bash` with no integrity check. For a tool that writes to `~/.claude/` and project directories, SHA256 verification is a reasonable expectation for security-conscious users."}],"common_pitfalls":[{"pitfall":"Ctrl+C orphans all `claude -p` subprocesses — they keep running and spending budget","affected_area":"ultrainit.sh startup, lib/agent.sh `run_agents_parallel()`","prevention":"Add at the top of ultrainit.sh: `trap 'kill 0' EXIT; trap 'exit 130' INT; trap 'exit 143' TERM`. `kill 0` kills the entire process group. Since `run_agents_parallel` child scripts are launched with `&` in a non-interactive shell (job control off), they remain in the parent's process group and will be terminated."},{"pitfall":"Target project's CLAUDE.md and hooks contaminate analysis agents","affected_area":"lib/agent.sh `run_agent()` — all claude -p invocations","prevention":"Add `--bare` to all `claude -p` calls in `run_agent()`. This skips loading the target project's `.claude/` config, MCP servers, hooks, memory, and CLAUDE.md during analysis. Verify structured output (`--json-schema`) still works with `--bare` before shipping."},{"pitfall":"bats `setup_file` variables not visible in `@test` bodies under `--jobs N`","affected_area":"tests/ — any new test files that use `setup_file`","prevention":"Always use `setup()` (per-test) for shared state, not `setup_file()`. Variables in `setup_file` must be `export`ed to reach `@test` bodies in parallel mode. The current architecture (`_common_setup()` called from `setup()`) is correct — preserve this pattern in new test files."},{"pitfall":"Schema validation under `--json-schema` uses retry loops — complex schemas increase cost unpredictably","affected_area":"schemas/*.json, lib/agent.sh `run_agent()`","prevention":"Keep schemas flat with minimal required fields. Avoid deeply nested required arrays. When a synthesis agent fails with `error_max_structured_output_retries`, the diagnosis agent in `diagnose_phase_failure()` should specifically flag this subtype and suggest schema simplification, not just show raw stderr."},{"pitfall":"`gensub()` in awk is gawk-only — silently broken on macOS stock awk and mawk","affected_area":"lib/*.sh — any awk invocation using gensub","prevention":"Add a gawk capability check to `check_dependencies()` in lib/config.sh: `awk 'BEGIN{gensub(/a/,\"b\",\"g\",\"t\")}' /dev/null 2>/dev/null || { log_error 'awk lacks gensub; install gawk'; missing=1; }`. In lib files, prefer `gsub()` (POSIX) over `gensub()` for simple replacements."},{"pitfall":"`sed -i` is mutually incompatible between GNU (Linux) and BSD (macOS)","affected_area":"lib/merge.sh, lib/validate.sh — any in-place file editing","prevention":"Replace `sed -i 'expr' file` with `tmp=$(mktemp); sed 'expr' <\"file\" >\"$tmp\" && mv \"$tmp\" \"file\"`. This is fully portable. The platform-detect-then-branch approach (`if [[ $PLATFORM == macos ]]`) is fragile across CI environments."},{"pitfall":"Large synthesis context (Pass 1 or Pass 2) passed via shell argument hits ARG_MAX","affected_area":"lib/synthesize.sh `run_synthesis_pass()` — large context string passed to `claude -p`","prevention":"The existing `run_agent()` already handles prompts >100KB via stdin piping. Ensure `run_synthesis_pass()` uses the same stdin pipe path for synthesis contexts, since they can easily exceed 100KB when accumulating findings from 30+ agents."},{"pitfall":"Background agent costs not counted before launching the next parallel batch — budget can overrun","affected_area":"lib/agent.sh `run_agents_parallel()`, lib/config.sh `check_budget()`","prevention":"Budget is checked per-agent at start of `run_agent()`. In parallel runs, all agents check budget simultaneously before any writes `.cost` files — so N agents can all pass the budget check and then all spend, overrunning by up to N×agent_budget. This is a known tradeoff. Document it explicitly in `check_budget()` as 'optimistic budget check under parallelism'."},{"pitfall":"bats-file and bats-support pinned to 'latest' in Dockerfile.test — can silently break on new releases","affected_area":"Dockerfile.test — bats helper library installation","prevention":"Pin bats-support, bats-assert, and bats-file to specific git SHAs or tags (e.g., `v0.3.0`) just as bats-core is pinned to `v1.11.1`. The current `HEAD` install is non-deterministic."}],"architectural_patterns":[{"pattern":"Scatter-gather with file-based coordination","applicability":"Directly implemented: Phase 1 scatters 8+ parallel `claude -p` workers, each writing findings to `.ultrainit/findings/{name}.json`. Phase 4 gathers all findings files into synthesis context. File-based coordination (vs in-memory channels) enables the resumability feature — if the script crashes, completed findings are preserved on disk."},{"pattern":"PATH-based binary mocking for CLI tool testing","applicability":"Directly implemented in tests/helpers/mock_claude.bash. A fake `claude` binary is placed earlier in `$PATH` than the real one. This is the standard pattern for testing tools that shell out to CLI programs, as opposed to function-level mocking (which doesn't work across `bash` subprocess boundaries). The dispatch-mode variant (per-agent response files) is a natural extension of this pattern."},{"pattern":"Fan-out with critical-path gating","applicability":"Directly implemented in lib/gather.sh. The 8 parallel agents all fan out simultaneously, but Stage 2 (deep-dive module agents) is gated on the `structure-scout` finding. `identity` and `structure-scout` are 'critical agents' — if either fails, the pipeline aborts rather than continuing with incomplete state. Non-critical agent failures (up to 2) allow the pipeline to proceed."},{"pattern":"Two-pass synthesis with inter-pass dependency","applicability":"Directly implemented in lib/synthesize.sh. Pass 1 (documentation) generates CLAUDE.md using all gathered evidence. Pass 2 (tooling) uses the Pass 1 output as its source of truth, ensuring skills/hooks/subagents are consistent with the generated documentation. This prevents the alternative failure mode: a single 1M-context pass trying to produce everything at once, which degrades output quality."},{"pattern":"Explicit environment propagation to child processes","applicability":"Directly implemented in `run_agents_parallel()`. Rather than relying on `export` or subshell inheritance, each parallel agent script has all parent environment variables baked in as literal values before re-sourcing lib files. This prevents a subtle bug: if `config.sh` re-runs `compute_budgets()` when sourced in the child, it would overwrite the parent's already-divided `AGENT_BUDGET`. Baking in the computed value prevents this."},{"pattern":"Progressive validation with targeted revision","applicability":"Directly implemented in lib/validate.sh + Phase 5. Only failing artifacts (skills, hooks, subagents that don't pass validation) are sent to a revision agent. Passing artifacts are preserved. This is more cost-efficient than re-running the entire synthesis pass on validation failure."}]},"terminal_reason":"completed","fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"83713c87-cbe1-4643-a889-52a5a5bc3e16"}
